<doc id="293511" wikidata="Q911268" url="?curid=293511" title="D'Alembert operator">
<text>In special relativity, electromagnetism and wave theory, the d&#x27;Alembert operator (denoted by a box: formula_1), also called the d&#x27;Alembertian, wave operator, box operator or sometimes quabla operator (&quot;cf&quot;. nabla symbol) is the Laplace operator of Minkowski space. The operator is named after French mathematician and physicist Jean le Rond d&#x27;Alembert.

In Minkowski space, in standard coordinates , it has the form
: formula_2

Here formula_3 is the 3-dimensional Laplacian and is the inverse Minkowski metric with 
:formula_4, formula_5, formula_6 for formula_7.
Note that the and summation indices range from 0 to 3: see Einstein notation. 

(Some authors alternatively use the negative metric signature of , with formula_8.)

Lorentz transformations leave the Minkowski metric invariant, so the d&#x27;Alembertian yields a Lorentz scalar. The above coordinate expressions remain valid for the standard coordinates in every inertial frame.

==The box symbol and alternate notations==
There are a variety of notations for the d&#x27;Alembertian. The most common are the &quot;box&quot; symbol formula_1 (Unicode: ) whose four sides represent the four dimensions of space-time and the &quot;box-squared&quot; symbol formula_10 which emphasizes the scalar property through the squared term (much like the Laplacian). In keeping with the triangular notation for the Laplacian, sometimes formula_11 is used.

Another way to write the d&#x27;Alembertian in flat standard coordinates is formula_12. This notation is used extensively in quantum field theory, where partial derivatives are usually indexed, so the lack of an index with the squared partial derivative signals the presence of the d&#x27;Alembertian.

Sometimes the box symbol is used to represent the four-dimensional Levi-Civita covariant derivative. The symbol formula_13 is then used to represent the space derivatives, but this is coordinate chart dependent.

==Applications==
The wave equation for small vibrations is of the form 
:formula_14
where is the displacement.

The wave equation for the electromagnetic field in vacuum is
:formula_15
where is the electromagnetic four-potential in Lorenz gauge.

The Klein–Gordon equation has the form
:formula_16

==Green&#x27;s function==
The Green&#x27;s function, formula_17, for the d&#x27;Alembertian is defined by the equation 
:formula_18

where formula_19 is the multidimensional Dirac delta function and formula_20 and formula_21 are two points in Minkowski space.

A special solution is given by the &quot;retarded Green&#x27;s function&quot; which corresponds to signal propagation only forward in time
:formula_22

where formula_23 is the Heaviside step function.

